I love Python, I really do, but JavaScript happens to be slightly better as a browser language because it is a little freer with the anonymous functions. Most JavaScript programmers use this all the time, without even thinking. Here's a jQuery example:<p>$.ajax({
  url: 'ajax/test.html',
  success: function(data) {
    $('.result').html(data);
    alert('Load was performed.');
  }
});<p>The equivalent Python would be this (assuming you ported jQuery):<p>def successcb(data):
    Q('.result').html(data)
    alert('Load was performed<p>Q.ajax(url='ajax/test.html', success = successcb)<p>OK, that's not too bad, I guess. Named parameters are nice. Having to define the success callback separately is not so great.<p>Edit, HN broke the formatting.
